The '''marsh tapaculo''' ('''''Scytalopus iraiensis''''') is a recently discovered [[passerine]] [[bird]] which belongs to the [[genus]] ''[[Scytalopus]]'', a genus of [[tapaculo]]s. It is also known as the '''wetland tapaculo''' or '''tall-grass wetland tapaculo'''. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Brazil]].

==Description==
It is a small, dumpy bird with broad tail-feathers and a total length of approximately 12.5&nbsp;cm. The upperparts are plain blackish in colour while the underparts are dark grey. The flanks are slightly barred with brown, at least in [[juvenile (organism)|young birds]]. The legs are reddish-brown and the bill is dark. The [[bird song|song]] includes a long series of short 'tchek' notes. The birds run rapidly and will fly short distances when flushed.{{Citation needed|date=May 2023}}

==Distribution and habitat==
It was first sighted on April 19, 1997&nbsp;in wetlands beside the [[Iraí River]] near [[Curitiba]] in southern Brazil. Until recently it was generally believed to be restricted to about two dozen sites in the eastern part of [[Paraná (state)|Paraná]] and [[Rio Grande do Sul]], but has now been discovered in the highlands of [[Minas Gerais]] – far north of its previously known range.{{Citation needed|date=May 2023}}

It occurs in seasonally flooded [[grassland]] in the [[floodplain]]s of rivers. It inhabits areas of tall (60–180&nbsp;cm), dense vegetation dominated by [[Cyperaceae|sedge]]s (such as ''[[Eleocharis]]'') and [[grass]]es. It forages at or near ground-level and feeds on small [[arthropod]]s, mainly insects such as [[Hemiptera|bugs]] and [[beetle]]s. Breeding occurs in late spring.{{Citation needed|date=May 2023}}

==Status and conservation==
It is classified as an [[endangered species]] due to its small and declining population and destruction of its [[habitat]]. Threats include [[drainage]], sand extraction, burning of grassland and the flooding of land due to the construction of [[dam]]s. Despite the recently discovered populations in Minas Gerais, some of which are within protected areas (the national parks of [[Serra do Cipó National Park|Serra do Cipó]] and [[Serra da Canastra National Park|Serra da Canastra]], and the private reserve [[Serra do Caraça]]), it has been recommended not downgrading it to a lower threatened status, but it remains to be seen if this will be followed.{{Citation needed|date=May 2023}}

